I believe this is because the type definition said that it had to be a PaginationArrow. But you are able to pass in your own component and as long as it has the properties in `PaginationArrowProps` then your component should work. title: [twitch-ext] Add typings for Twitch Extension helper
body:
:wave: Hi there!

I've been using this in our [Twitch Extension](https://github.com/hearthsim/twitch-hdt-frontend) for quite some time, and have now polished the typings for submission here. The typings refer to the [Twitch Extension Javascript Helper](https://dev.twitch.tv/docs/extensions/reference/#javascript-helper
), which is a CDN-provided file that is loaded by every Twitch Extension. Twitch Extensions are small bundles containing some Javascript that are uploaded to [Twitch](https://www.twitch.tv/) that broadcasters can enable on their channel for some interactive features. The helper typed in this PR is used to facilitate some of the interactive features and provide the extension with some contextual details so it can optimize how it displays itself.

I typed based on the official documentation (especially for most of the comments), but to my best knowledge it is correct as it works in our application. The package name here is based on the actual Javascript helper file ([https://extension-files.twitch.tv/helper/v1/twitch-ext.min.js](https://extension-files.twitch.tv/helper/v1/twitch-ext.min.js)), and that's also where the version comes from (the same as reported by `Twitch.ext.version`).

I'm pretty happy with where this is, and I think I've resolved most of the typing uncertainties I had. There's one function in here where I'm not quite sure and the typing could probaby be improved, which is `onContext`: The existance of a property in `changed` guarantees that it exists in `context` - I tried to map that with the generic `<T extends Partial<TwitchContext>>`, but I'm not sure whether there's a more elegant way.

Either way, looking forward to feedback and seeing this released!

Basically, page has exported a `default` for a while in the form of `exports.default`. So in TS we should actually be importing like so:

```ts
import page from 'page';
```

Rather than:

```ts
import * as page from 'page';
```

The latter works but doesn't make much sense against ES modules as you shouldn't be able to invoke a namespace (`page()`).
